{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KYHNjFyPBqtp8DZjE8JmLf","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file written at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/10-4-rust-provider.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 10-4-rust-provider with 27 acceptance criteria, 19 tasks, full technical notes, and source extraction mapping. All ACs tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` since every criterion can be verified by instantiating the provider and calling methods in unit tests -- no external system interaction required.\n\nKey details:\n- 27 ACs covering all `StackProvider` methods, edge cases for Cargo.toml parsing, workspace aggregation, and registration\n- 19 tasks following the exact pattern from stories 10-2 (NodejsProvider) and 10-3 (PythonProvider)\n- 2 new shared utils (`getCargoDepsSection`, `hasCargoDep`) extracted from `stack-detect.ts` into `utils.ts`\n- 4 files to change: `rust.ts` (create), `utils.ts` (modify), `index.ts` (modify), `rust.test.ts` (create)\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity in epic definition:** The original story notes mention `'library'` AppType for Rust, but the `AppType` union in `src/lib/stacks/types.ts` has no `'library'` variant -- only `'generic'`. The existing `stack-detect.ts` code maps `[lib]` to `'generic'`. I followed the actual code behavior (returns `'generic'`), not the story notes. If `'library'` is needed as a distinct AppType, that requires a types.ts change which should be a separate story.\n- **Bevy system libs:** The original story notes mention Bevy detection for Docker system libs, but no such logic exists in the current `dockerfile-template.ts`. I explicitly deferred this to avoid scope creep. Documented in Technical Notes.\n- **Risk -- workspace aggregation ordering:** The story notes say \"cargo workspace aggregation must fire before any other parser -- this ordering guard is critical.\" In the provider pattern, each provider has its own `parseTestOutput()`, so there's no cross-provider ordering concern. The aggregation regex with global flag and iteration handles workspace output correctly within the Rust provider alone. No risk here.\n- **Observation:** All 27 ACs are `cli-verifiable`. Rust provider has no external system dependencies for unit testing since `installOtlp()` and `detectCoverageConfig()` (which shells out to `cargo tarpaulin --version` in the consumer) can be tested by mocking or by testing the file-reading path only. The provider's `detectCoverageConfig()` differs from the consumer's -- it reads Cargo.toml presence rather than executing `cargo tarpaulin --version`."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a51b3e753372d4009 (use SendMessage with to: 'a51b3e753372d4009' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 72640\ntool_uses: 23\nduration_ms: 152671</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1d547185-a995-481d-9659-9279ed70f717","uuid":"e52c4164-7ffd-4f76-aafc-394b06f76fa0","timestamp":"2026-03-24T09:14:24.408Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 10-4-rust-provider. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that